Useful little partnership for the final wicket there - in the end both teams will be fairly happy with how the Pakistan innings unfolded. Wickets are falling rapidly under the dank Headingley skies so Pakistan's 170 lead is plenty. That said, Australia know if they can build a lead of 100 in their second innings, it could be enough. Cracking Test so far, we're only midway through the second day and two innings are already completed.

With the best part of two sessions remaining today, could we see a repeat of this? Given how Pakistan bowled first-up, I wouldn't entirely rule it out ... ps ... how is that match a full ten years old already?

Gnasher is barely able to contain his excitement about the chance of a two-day Test and you can read his views on it all in his end-of-innings bulletin, which will be ready shortly.

And that will be lunch on day two. Pakistan have taken their lead to 130 in this shortened first session, but they've had a chunk taken out of their middle order with Umars Amin and Akmal dismissed and the responsibility will now rest with Shoaib Malik and Kamran Akmal to bat their team into an invincible position.

Australia have been fairly flat in the gloom, with only Hilfenhaus and Watson getting the old ball to move in seam-friendly conditions. The Australian attack has been unusually erratic, and 26 extras have already been gifted to Pakistan. Torquaychad hasn't been the least bit impressed by the bowling this morning: "Johnson & Bollinger should open a pie shop together the way they've been bowling!"

Andrew McGlashan's lunchtime bulletin has just landed, hot off the press!

"Perhaps Tourquaychad should have said Johnston and Bollinger should open a "pi shop" being international pi day (22/7)," retorts John.

Rehman reminds us what a good game Salman Butt is having in his first match as Test captain: "Everyone's talking about how batsmen played or how bowlers bowled. But noone mentioned the Pakistan's Captain Salman Butt. He's the one in-charged, the credit for Pakistan's super strong position SHOULD go in Salman Butt's name. I'm just saying"

Waqar knows there's still a lot of cricket to be played in this game: "I see that Pakistan right now have the lead, but i don't think Pakistan is in a good position to win this match, yet. Pakistan is a really unpredictable team. One moment they are dominant and before you know it they come crashing down."

"Pakistan are not in the dominant position yet," adds Amer. "There is alot of depth in Aussie batting and you can never forget Sydney Test either!"

3.41pm Good news, the covers are being rolled back and a rope is going round the outfield. We may be back on soon. In fact, if things remain as they are, we will be back on at 3.50pm. And that's a fact.

3.27pm Brydon is back after stocking up on tea and cake, and informs us that the covers are still in place and the rain is still spitting down. We will be held up for a while, but Australia won't mind that on two fronts. Not least, it might liven up the wicket a touch.

3.21pm The covers came out as the players went off for the break, and there appears to be some drizzle in the air. We'll update you as soon as we know what the weather's doing!

Meanwhile, Nirav has been daydreaming: "The super-ultimate extra-ordinaire sub-continent team comprising of Indian batsmen, Sri Lankan spinners, and Pakistani pacers: Gambhir, Sehwag, Dravid, Tendulkar, Laxman, Dhoni, Herath, Mendis, Aamer, Asif, and Gul." Personally I'd have Sangakkara in there in place of the million-dollar man, but otherwise, it's hard to fault that line-up!

So, that's tea on day one. Pakistan's openers survive until the interval and they've done superbly to cement their side's dominant position in this game. Australia's bowlers haven't quite found their rhythm at all yet, and the match is steadily slipping away from them. Before play starts again, there's certainly enough time to give Andrew McGlashan's teatime bulletin a read.
